                        <td>
                        <font class = headline>The Mob Just Poofed! Where did it go?</font><br>
                        <IMG
                            SRC="Not Used"
                            BORDER="0"
                            ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE="20" VSPACE="10">
                       <font size = 2 face = arial color = black>Posted by: necrro</font><br> 
                       <font size = 1 face = arial color = black>Posted on: Mon Jul  1 21:46:22 2002</font><br><br> 
                       As you know, in some zones, especially Kunark ones like OverThere and Timorous Deep, you can be fighting a mob who gets down to about 10% hp and all of a sudden poofs away from you even though you still have it targeted. Not only is this frustrating, but it allows the mob time to heal (unless you have a handy DoT applied to it).<br><br>Where did that mob go? Almost always the mob goes back to its spawn point. So while in these types of zones, try not to pull to far from the mob's spawn point (Spirocs in Tim Deep are a good e.g.).<br><br>But you say, "Necro what about those pesky gators in Oasis who have no spawn point and are roamers?<br><br>In fact all mobs have some spawn point whether they are roamers or even whether they have a random spawn point that continually changes. The fact is in such a case you must run around hoping to reaquire that mob.<br><br>A word of caution, sometimes when the mob poofs its aggro list gets wiped. Unfortunately, your DoT may not have been wiped. Thus, you must do something to that mob to get the exp for it. I have seen a mob poof and die at its spawn point and me get no exp. Wiping of aggro lists means the credit for the kill is awarded to no one, or worse yet any passerby who happens to do at least 1 hp of damage. When you reacquire that mob, do some damage, a non-damage spell may not be enough.<br><br>You may say, "but wait a minute, if my DoT is still there and kills him at his spawn point, why don't I still get exp? It's my DoT!" When an aggro list gets created you are put on that list by the first action you take ( cast a spell on it whether resisted or not). If the list is wiped, the DoT, that is still working, technically has no owner. If this were not true and DoT's or charms created new aggro every tick, using one of these spells would be suicide.<br><br>Aggro generally works like this....Mob starts out with blank slate of aggro list with only a certain number of possible entries (rumored to be between 5-10). You then find your way on aggro list by:<br><br>1. Coming within aggro range of a mob on whose @#%$ list you reside (bad faction).<br><br>2. Attack the mob (debuff, nuke, melee, bows, etc.).<br><br>3. Heal or beneficially affect or help someone attacking the mob.<br><br>Now you are on list based upon the first action you took from the above list. I wont get into it here, but each action or spell, etc. has a certain amount of aggro assigned to it. That will affect who the mob goes after in a multiple aggro listing situation (e.g. - a whole group does some kind of damage to a particular mob).<br><br>Once on the list, you can be moved up or down from the first to the last position or even off the list in raid situations because the aggro value and list keeps changing and becoming modified by all the players actions who are attacking the mob.<br><br>Regardless of how the aggro list is developed, if it is wiped due to a player action (mem wipe by Chanter/Necro) or by game mechanics (poof), all the players who did any damage to the mob now receive no credit for it because the list is blank and exp is awarded on a kill to the person on the list that did the most damage. There is noone on the list after a wipe.<br><br>Of course this has implications for other aspects of the game like charming. When you charm a mob who does say 80% of the damage to another mob you are fighting and the Charm wears off, you have two options:<br><br>1. Kill the mob you charmed first.<br><br>2. Re-charm the mob who was initially your pet.<br><br>If you do niether, and say decide to kill the original target who is now down to 20% hp, you will not get exp because your originally charmed mob took all the credit for the damage he did when charmed with him when he broke charm. You must recharm him to get that credit for damage back or kill him first thereby wiping him from the credit for damage list (aggro) of the originally target mob that is now at 20% hp. Its all a matter of timing.<br><br>As an ENC I charm soloed the zone to Lower Guk alot from 34-41. I would run into situations where I let my pet get beat on bad, then kill the original target and park my pet down the ramp a sec while I med. I dispell him to break charm, he is low on hp and some dude comes along to help me and whacks the now uncharmed mob who is very low hp. I get Ks'd because the uncharmed mob has a blank aggro list/exp slate and is low hp. So the first person who does the most damage to him gets exp.<br><br>Just some food for thought.<br><br> 
                       Necrro 53rd Heretic (Misty Knight)<br>
